@NODE EUsage
Quick-Documentation

- Copy the whole directory whereever you want it to with Drag and Drop.
  All important files would be transfered in that way.
  Be aware, that WordWrapGUI and WordWrap are in the same directory!

- Start the program "WordWrapGUI" via Double-Click on the program-
  icon. After a succesful start a window will appear on the screen.

- Select via mouse-click the desired options.
  When you have selected an option, you can not disable it again - you
  can choose between the two buttons with the same meaning.
  (In GUI appear icons instead of characters)

                         +-----+-----+-----+-----+
                         | -h  | -i  | -m  |     |
                         +-----+-----+-----+-----+
                         | -H  | -ia | -M  |Load |
                         +-----+-----+-----+-----+
                       @{"Meaning" LINK EBedeutung}

- Open (after choosing some options) the file with the original text.
  It will appear another window then (no file-requester, sorry  ;->).

- When you enterd the path and file-name, press enter. That will start the
  command wordwrap.
  In an extra window the syntax of the command appear to check the 
  structure of the command - feel this as an education.

- The changed file will be put in the same path as the original file.
  The name will be changed by an additional '.ww' at the end of the file
  name, only.

- You can break the program WordWrapGUI by typing CTRL-C or use the Close-
  Gadget


PS: The use of WordWrapGUI reduces the possibility in selection of options
    in comparison with the shell-command wordwrap.
    The options will be transfered with fixed values.
    You should use the {"Shell-Command" link EBedeutung} wordwrap, when
    you are more experienced with WordWrapGUI.

@ENDNODE

@NODE EBedeutung
In GUI you have the following options:

 *   -h         try to put hyphenated words back together
 *   -H         like -h, but never removes the hyphens themselves
     -b         protect blank lines
     -l  [75]   output line length, defaults to 75
 *   -i         protect indentation
 *   -ia          "        "  + adding a blank line before each paragraph
     -t  [ 8]   how to expand tab characters in the left margin
 *   -m  [ 8]   add a left margin of 8 characters
 *   -M  [ 8]   ignore a left margin on the input of 8 characters
     -s  [75]   protect short input line: a line of 75 chars remains short

 * = can be selected in GUI via mouse-click.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
The Shell-Command is more powerful: 23 options are available:

     -l<len>         output line length, defaults to 75
     -b              protect blank lines
     -bc[<indent>]   convert blank lines to indentation
     -bC[<indent>]   like -bc, but don't indent after group of blank lines
     -i              protect indentation
     -i<indent>       " , enforcing a fixed indentation width
     -ia             \\_ the same as -i, but adding a
     -ia<indent>     /  blank line before each paragraph.
     -ic             convert indentations to blank lines
     -t<tabsize>     how to expand tab characters in the left margin
     -m<width>       add a left margin
     -M<width>       ignore a left margin on the input
     -s<maxlen>      protect short input lines
     -e<parno>       enable escape mode for one paragraph
     -h              try to put hyphenated words back together
     -H              like -h, but never removes the hyphens themselves
     -w              two spaces after ".", "!" and "?"
     -W              two spaces after ".", "!", "?" and ":"
     -n              make non-breakable space (alt-sp: 0xa0) breakable
     -a<dstring>     delimiter string" that will always start a new line
     -z<dstring>      " , always ending an output line
     -A<dword>       like -a, but only matches against whole words
     -Z<dword>       like -z,  "
@ENDNODE

